	isbn = {978-1-118-77837-1},
	abstract = {Summary The atmosphere over sea ice comprises a complex but important system of linked processes impacting the sea ice. Atmospheric energy fluxes explain much of the annual cycle of sea-ice mass balance, while atmospheric momentum flux is a primary parameter governing the movement of sea ice. Key atmospheric components include the structure and stability of the atmospheric boundary layer, cloud macro- and microphysics, vertical mixing processes, and free-tropospheric advection of heat, moisture, and aerosols. Radiative and turbulent energy fluxes are key for the surface energy budget. Interactions between atmospheric radiative and turbulent processes and sea-ice surface characteristics, such as melt ponds, snow cover, and leads, determine the quantitative impacts on sea-ice mass balance. Atmospheric boundary-layer stability and processes modulate momentum transport. Several atmospheric components, such as cloud structure and stable boundary-layer mixing, are poorly represented in models, producing erroneous fluxes in regional and global climate models and in reanalyses.},
