	issn = {15580644},
	doi = {10.1109/TGRS.2021.3103417},
	abstract = {Observations of microwave backscatter from shoaling and breaking surface waves acquired with a shore-based, coherent-on-receive X-band marine radar are presented. The radar was located at the dune cliff of a sandy beach with two breaker bars. Waves were approximately shore-normal (inclination \&lt; 10\&\#x00B0;) during the study period. Consistent with other studies, the backscatter intensity from breaking waves is significantly increased (\&\#x2248;10 dB compared to nonbreaking) with Doppler velocities close to the wave phase velocity in shallow water. The strong backscatter from active breakers can cause a significant amount of signal artifacts due to the leakage of pulse energy into adjacent range cells, in particular behind the breaking crests. In the near range, the backscatter from the undisturbed surface and such pulse smearing artifacts appear as distinct peaks inside the Doppler spectra. Thus, the velocity of both sources of scatterering can be retrieved using a dedicated peak separation algorithm. In the far range (r \&gt; 500 m), the artifacts dominate the Doppler signal behind breaking wave crests. Therefore, when investigating the spatio-temporal evolution of breaking wave-induced Doppler velocities with marine radar, the analysis should be restricted to the wave crests and the well-illuminated front faces of the waves. The evolution of Doppler spectra tracked along the crest of an exemplary individual breaking wave is extracted during the steepening, active- and post-breaking stage.},
