	abstract = {Tilt invariance is a stringent but necessary condition that a second-order{\textbackslash}nwave scattering model must satisfy in order to qualify for a broad{\textbackslash}nrange of applications. This invariance expresses the fact that the{\textbackslash}nscattering model is unchanged whether the tilting of the scattering{\textbackslash}nsurface is implemented before or after its reduction to the limit{\textbackslash}nof the small-perturbation method (SPM). Our scattering model is based{\textbackslash}non a second-order kernel which is quadratic in its lowest order with{\textbackslash}nrespect to successive derivatives of the rough surface. Hence, it{\textbackslash}nis termed the local curvature approximation (LCA). We have previously{\textbackslash}ndemonstrated that the LCA is approximately tilt invariant in the{\textbackslash}nquasi-specular and quasi-backscattering geometries. In this contribution,{\textbackslash}nLCA is made formally tilt invariant up to first order in the tilting{\textbackslash}nvector. It will be shown that this formal tilt invariance is achieved{\textbackslash}nmainly through inclusion of polarization mixing due to out-of-plane{\textbackslash}ntilt. Even though the LCA formally reduces to the SPM and Kirchhoff{\textbackslash}nlimits in addition to tilt invariance, its curvature kernel stays{\textbackslash}nreasonably concise and practical to implement in both analytical{\textbackslash}nand numerical evaluations. This curvature kernel may also be used{\textbackslash}nin the other two formulations of our model, namely the nonlocal curvature{\textbackslash}napproximation and the weighted curvature approximation},
