	abstract = {The principle of conservation of action is applied to derive a spectral form for short, wind-generated waves on the ocean which is valid to second order in the slopes of longer surface waves. Using this form, composite surface theory is applied to microwave backscatter from the ocean surface in the Bragg regime to derive an expression for the normalized radar cross section of the sea, σ0, which is also valid to second order in long-wave slope. This expression is compared with previous data and empirical models of σ0 and is shown to account for the observed incidence angle, azimuth angle, wind speed, and polarization dependence. Comparisons are made at Ku and C band for incidence angles between 20° and 70°. The theory indicates the manner in which atmospheric stability, long-wave spectra, and sea surface temperature may influence σ0. Upwind-downwind asymmetry of σ0 is shown to occur because of the second-order interaction of short-wave modulation with the orbital velocities of long waves. Furthermore, the results suggest that the wind speed dependence of σ0 varies only slightly with microwave frequency, while the magnitude of σ0 increases somewhat with frequency until viscous or turbulent dissipation reduces short-wave growth rates and thus amplitudes. Implications for scatterometer algorithm development are discussed.},
