	abstract = {The influence of wind stress, small-scale waves, and surface films{\textbackslash}non air-sea gas exchange at low to moderate wind speeds ({\textless}10 m s-1){\textbackslash}nis examined. Coincident observations of wind stress, heat transfer{\textbackslash}nvelocity, surface wave slope, and surface film enrichments were made{\textbackslash}nin coastal and offshore waters south of Cape Cod, New England, in{\textbackslash}nJuly 1997 as part of the NSF-CoOP Coastal Air-Sea Chemical Fluxes{\textbackslash}nstudy. Gas transfer velocities have been extrapolated from aqueous{\textbackslash}nheat transfer velocities derived from infrared imagery and direct{\textbackslash}ncovariance and bulk heat flux estimates. Gas transfer velocity is{\textbackslash}nfound to follow a quadratic relationship with wind speed, which accounts{\textbackslash}nfor 75-77\% of the variance but which overpredicts transfer velocity{\textbackslash}nin the presence of surface films. The dependence on wind stress as{\textbackslash}nrepresented by the friction velocity is also nonlinear, reflecting{\textbackslash}na wave field-dependent transition between limiting transport regimes.{\textbackslash}nIn contrast, the dependence on mean square slope computed for the{\textbackslash}nwave number range of 40-800 rad m-1 is found to be linear and in{\textbackslash}nagreement with results from previous laboratory wind wave studies.{\textbackslash}nThe slope spectrum of the small-scale waves and the gas transfer{\textbackslash}nvelocity are attenuated in the presence of surface films. Observations{\textbackslash}nover large-scale gradients of biological productivity and dissolved{\textbackslash}norganic matter show that the reduction in slope and transfer velocity{\textbackslash}nare more clearly correlated with surface film enrichments than with{\textbackslash}nbulk organic matter concentrations. The mean square slope parameterization{\textbackslash}nexplains 89-95\% of the observed variance in th